Reasoning: The paper proposes a novel crowdsourcing framework that intelligently assigns tasks to workers to reduce latencies and meet expected accuracies. This involves designing a task scheduler module and a notification module. The paper focuses on improving the efficiency and effectiveness of crowdsourcing, which falls under the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves machine learning techniques such as kernel density estimation, which falls under the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The design of the task scheduler module involves solving an NP-hard problem, which falls under the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also involves social computing aspects such as worker behavior and task acceptance probabilities, which falls under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves security and privacy concerns related to crowdsourcing, which falls under the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category.
